Here's a full Java program that reads a JSON file from a source folder, converts it to XML, and writes it to a destination folder.


---

‚úÖ Requirements:

1. Java SDK 8 or above.


2. External libraries:

org.json (for JSON parsing)

json.org also supports XML conversion via org.json.XML




You can add this dependency via Maven or manually include the jar file:

<!-- Add to your pom.xml if using Maven -->
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.json</groupId>
    <artifactId>json</artifactId>
    <version>20240303</version> <!-- Or latest -->
</dependency>


---

üìÅ Folder Structure Example:

sourceFolder/data.json

Output will go to: destinationFolder/data.xml



---

‚úÖ Java Code

import org.json.JSONObject;
import org.json.XML;

import java.io.IOException;
import java.nio.file.Files;
import java.nio.file.Paths;
import java.nio.file.Path;

public class JsonToXmlConverter {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String sourceFolder = "sourceFolder";               // Replace with your source path
        String destinationFolder = "destinationFolder";     // Replace with your destination path
        String fileName = "data.json";                      // Replace with your JSON file name

        Path jsonFilePath = Paths.get(sourceFolder, fileName);
        Path xmlFilePath = Paths.get(destinationFolder, fileName.replace(".json", ".xml"));

        try {
            // Read JSON content
            String jsonContent = new String(Files.readAllBytes(jsonFilePath));

            // Convert JSON to XML
            JSONObject jsonObject = new JSONObject(jsonContent);
            String xmlContent = XML.toString(jsonObject, "root"); // "root" is the XML root tag

            // Write XML to file
            Files.createDirectories(xmlFilePath.getParent()); // Ensure destination folder exists
            Files.write(xmlFilePath, xmlContent.getBytes());

            System.out.println("Conversion complete. XML file written to: " + xmlFilePath);
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.err.println("File error: " + e.getMessage());
        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.err.println("Conversion error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}


---

üìù Notes:

Change fileName to read different JSON files dynamically.

To convert multiple JSON files, wrap the logic inside a loop scanning the source folder using Files.list(Paths.get(sourceFolder)).


